# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] It takes its name from the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which had substantially different boundaries.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The Aberdeenshire Council area includes all of the areas of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire except the area making up Aberdeen City Council area, as well as part of Banffshire.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The historic county boundaries are still officially used for a few purposes, namely land registration and lieutenancy.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire Council is headquartered at Woodhill House in Aberdeen, making it the only Scottish council whose headquarters are located outside its jurisdiction.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeen itself forms a different council area (Aberdeen City).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire borders onto Angus and Perth and Kinross to the south, Highland and Moray to the west and Aberdeen City to the east.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Traditionally, it has depended economically on the primary sector (agriculture, fishing, and forestry) and related processing industries.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Over the last 40 years, the development of the oil and gas industry and associated service sector has broadened Aberdeenshire's economic base, and contributed to a rapid population growth of some 50% since 1975.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Its land represents 8% of Scotland's overall territory.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] It covers an area of 6,313 square kilometres (2,437 sq mi).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a rich prehistoric and historical heritage.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] It is the locus of a large number of Neolithic and Bronze Age archaeological sites, including Longman Hill, Kempstone Hill, Catto Long Barrow and Cairn Lee.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The area was settled in the Bronze Age by the Beaker culture, who arrived from the south around 2000–1800 BC.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Stone circles and cairns were constructed predominantly in this era.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Around the 1st century AD, the Taexali people, who left little history, were believed to have resided along the coast.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The Picts were the next documented inhabitants of the area and were no later than 800–900 AD.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The Romans also were in the area during this period, as they left signs at Kintore.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Christianity influenced the inhabitants early on, and there were Celtic monasteries at Old Deer and Monymusk.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Since medieval times, there have been many traditional paths that crossed the Mounth (a spur of mountainous land that extends from the higher inland range to the North Sea slightly north of Stonehaven) through present-day Aberdeenshire from the Scottish Lowlands to the Highlands.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Some of the most well known and historically important trackways are the Causey Mounth and Elsick Mounth.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire played an important role in the fighting between the Scottish dynasties.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] During the Anglo-Norman penetration, other families arrive, such as House of Balliol, Clan Bruce, and Clan Cumming (Comyn).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] During the Scottish Wars of Independence, the King of England Edward I travelled across the area twice with his invading army, in 1296 and 1303.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] In 1307, Robert the Bruce was victorious near Inverurie.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] These new families set the stage for the upcoming rivalries during the 14th and 15th centuries.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] This rivalry grew worse during and after the Protestant Reformation when religion was another reason for conflict between the clans.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The Gordon family adhered to Catholicism and the Forbeses to Protestantism.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire was the historic seat of the clan Dempster.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Three universities were founded in the area prior to the 17th century, King's College in Old Aberdeen (1494), Marischal College in Aberdeen (1593), and the University of Fraserburgh (1592).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] During the 17th century, Aberdeenshire was the location of more fighting, centred on the Marquess of Montrose and the Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] This period also saw increased wealth due to the increase in trade with Germany, Poland, and the Low Countries.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] After the end of the Revolution of 1688, an extended peaceful period was interrupted only by fleeting events such as the Rising of 1715 and the Rising of 1745.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The latter resulted in the end of the ascendancy of Episcopalianism and the feudal power of landowners.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] An era began of increased agricultural and industrial progress.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The present council area is named after the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which has different boundaries and ceased to be used for local government purposes in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Local government functions were shared between the two levels.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The modern council area was created in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] It covers the combined area of the Banff and Buchan, Gordon, and Kincardine and Deeside districts that had been created in 1975.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The present Aberdeenshire Council area therefore consists of all of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire (except the area of those two counties making up Aberdeen City), as well as the north-east portions of Banffshire.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The population of the council area has risen over 50% since 1971 to approximately 265,080 in 2024, representing 4.7% of Scotland's total.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's population has increased by 9.1% since 2001, while Scotland's total population grew by 3.8%.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The census lists a relatively high proportion of under 16s and slightly fewer working-age people compared with the Scottish average.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is one of the most homogeneous/indigenous regions of the UK.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] In 2011, 82.2% of residents identified as 'White Scottish', followed by 12.3% who are 'White British', whilst ethnic minorities constitute only 0.9% of the population.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The largest ethnic minority group is Asian Scottish/British at 0.8%.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] In addition to the English language, 48.8% of residents reported being able to speak and understand the Scots language.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,382 residents aged three and over, 121,797 (47.5%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] This is the greatest proportion of Scots speakers of any Scottish council area.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,377 residents aged three and over, 3,579 (1.4%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is estimated at £3,496M (2011), representing 5.2% of the Scottish total.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy is closely linked to Aberdeen City's (GDP £7,906M), and in 2011, the region as a whole was calculated to contribute 16.8% of Scotland's GDP.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Between 2012 and 2014, the combined Aberdeenshire and Aberdeen City economic forecast GDP growth rate is 8.6%, the highest growth rate of any local council area in the UK and above the Scottish rate of 4.8%.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] A significant proportion of Aberdeenshire's working residents commute to Aberdeen City for work, varying from 11.5% from Fraserburgh to 65% from Westhill.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Average Gross Weekly Earnings (for full-time employees employed in workplaces in Aberdeenshire in 2011) are £572.60.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the Scottish average by £2.10 and a fall of 2.6% on the 2010 figure.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The average gross weekly pay of people resident in Aberdeenshire is much higher, at £741.90, as many people commute out of Aberdeenshire, principally into Aberdeen City.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Total employment (excluding farm data) in Aberdeenshire is estimated at 93,700 employees (Business Register and Employment Survey 2009).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The majority of employees work within the service sector, predominantly in public administration, education and health.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Almost 19% of employment is within the public sector.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy remains closely linked to Aberdeen City's and the North Sea oil industry, with many employees in oil-related jobs.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] The average monthly unemployment (claimant count) rate for Aberdeenshire in 2011 was 1.5%.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the average rate of Aberdeen City (2.3%), Scotland (4.2%) and the UK (3.8%).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] In the 2014 Scottish independence referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'No' by a percentage of 60.4%.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] In the 2016 European Union membership referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'Remain' by the third lowest margin of 55.0%.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] First and second lowest margin for 'Remain' were Moray (50.1%) and Dumfries and Galloway (53.1%).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] There are numerous rivers and burns in Aberdeenshire, including Cowie Water, Carron Water, Burn of Muchalls, River Dee, River Don, River Ury, River Ythan, Water of Feugh, Burn of Myrehouse, Laeca Burn and Luther Water.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Numerous bays and estuaries are found along the seacoast of Aberdeenshire, including Banff Bay, Ythan Estuary, Stonehaven Bay and Thornyhive Bay.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a marine west coast climate on the Köppen climate classification.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is in the rain shadow of the Grampians, therefore it has a generally dry climate for a maritime region, with portions of the coast receiving 25 inches (64 cm) of moisture annually.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Summers are mild, and winters are typically cold in Aberdeenshire; Coastal temperatures are moderated by the North Sea such that coastal areas are typically cooler in the summer and warmer in the winter than inland locations.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/aberdeenshire] Coastal areas are also subject to haar, or coastal fog.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/ada-of-scotland] Ada was born in Scotland, the daughter of Henry of Huntingdon and Ada de Warenne.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/ada-of-scotland] Henry was the son of King David I of Scotland and Maud, Countess of Huntingdon, and Ada's siblings include the Scottish kings Malcolm IV, William the Lion, and David of Scotland, Earl of Huntingdon.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/ada-of-scotland] In 1162 she was asked for her hand in marriage to Floris III, Count of Holland by the Abbot of Egmond, Holland.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/ada-of-scotland] Together, the Abbot and Ada traveled back to Holland, where the wedding ceremony occurred, probably in Egmond, on 28 August 1162.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/ada-of-scotland] Ada received the County of Ross in the Scottish Highlands as a wedding gift.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/ada-of-scotland] Ada was not actively involved in the governance of the County of Holland but was occasionally mentioned in documents.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/ada-of-scotland] Floris, her husband was a loyal ally of the Holy Roman Emperor, Frederick I, and often went with him into battle.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/ada-of-scotland] Dutch chronicler Melis Stoke states that she supported her son in the war with William of Cleves during the War of Succession.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/ada-of-scotland] In addition, Ada is known to have read Latin.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/ada-of-scotland] Ada died after 1206 and was probably buried in the Abbey of Middelburg, to which she had already made donations of £64.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/ada-of-scotland] Ada and Floris had about 11 children, some of whom died young.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters allowed cultivation at much greater heights and made land more productive.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open-field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism from the twelfth century.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for oats.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] New monastic orders such as the Cistercians became major landholders and sheep farmers, particularly in the Borders where they were organised in granges.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the late Medieval period, most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams, allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, known as husbandmen.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised for meat.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The rural economy appears to have boomed in the thirteenth century and in the immediate aftermath of the Black Death was still buoyant, but by the 1360s there was a severe falling off in incomes to be followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Scotland is roughly half the size of England and Wales and has approximately the same amount of coastline, but only between a fifth and a sixth of the amount of the arable or good pastoral land, under 60 metres above sea level, and most of this is located in the south and east.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This made marginal pastoral farming and fishing, the key factors in the pre-modern economy.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Its east Atlantic position means that it has moderate rainfall: today about 700 mm per year in the east and over 1,000 mm in the west.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This encouraged the spread of blanket peat bog, the acidity of which, combined with high level of wind and salt spray, made most of the western islands treeless.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The existence of hills, mountains, quicksands and marshes made agriculture and internal communication difficult.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The early Middle Ages, from the fifth century to the tenth century, were a period of climate deterioration, with a drop in temperature and an increase in rainfall, resulting in more land becoming unproductive.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] With a lack of significant transport links and wider markets, most farms had to produce a self-sufficient diet of meat, dairy products and cereals, supplemented by hunter-gathering.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The climate meant that more oats and barley were grown than wheat.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The evidence of bones indicates that cattle were by far the most important domesticated animal, followed by pigs, sheep and goats, while domesticated fowl were very rare.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Christian missionaries from Ireland may have changed agricultural practice, bringing innovations such as the horizontal watermill and mould board ploughs, which were more effective in turning the soil.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters of the Medieval Warm Period allowed cultivation at much greater heights above sea level and made land more productive.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas in the south and east than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The feudalism introduced under David I, particularly in the east and south where the crown's authority was greatest, saw the placement of baronial lordships.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Land was now held from the king, or a superior lord, in exchange for loyalty and forms of service that were usually military.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Barons, who held feudal tenures, had the right to hold baronial courts, which could deal with matters of land ownership.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the imposition of feudalism continued to sit beside the existing systems of landholding and tenure and it is not clear how this change impacted on the lives of the ordinary free and unfree workers.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In places, feudalism may have tied workers more closely to the land.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the predominantly pastoral nature of Scottish agriculture may have made the imposition of a manorial system, based on the English model, impracticable in some areas.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Obligations appear to have been limited to occasional labour service, seasonal renders of food, hospitality and money rents.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually included supplying oxen for ploughing the lord's land on an annual basis and the much resented obligation to grind corn at the lord's mill.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones, creating large tracts of land reserved for the leisure of the aristocracy and nobility.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were less rigorously enforced than in England, where the taking of wood and game were strictly forbidden, and all royal forests were on land already in the king's hands.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The introduction of new monastic orders such as the Cistercians in this period also brought innovations in agriculture.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Particularly in the Borders, their monasteries became major landholders, sheep farmers and producers of wool for the markets in Flanders.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were organised in granges, monastic farms run by lay brothers of the order.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Granges were theoretically within 30 miles of the mother monastery, so that those working there could return for services on Sundays and feast days.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were used for variety of purposes, including pastoral, arable and industrial production.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, to manage more distant assets in Ayrshire, Melrose Abbey used Mauchline as a "super grange", to oversee lesser granges.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Some abbeys like Melrose had at least 12,000 sheep in the late thirteenth century.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism and would continue until the eighteenth century.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This expanded from the use of small enclosed fields, which continued from the prehistoric era.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The infield was the best land, close to housing.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was farmed continuously and most intensively, receiving most of the manure.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were usually bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for largely for oats.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was fertilised from the overnight folding of cattle in the summer and was often left fallow to recover its fertility.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In fertile regions the infield could be extensive, but in the uplands it might be small, surrounded by large amounts of outfield.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In coastal areas fertiliser included seaweed and around the major burghs urban refuse was used.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Yields were fairly low, often around three times the quantity of seed sown, although they could reach twice that yield on some infields.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The main unit of land measurement in Scotland was the *davoch* (i.e.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This unit is also known as the "Scottish ploughgate".
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In English-speaking Lothian, it was simply a ploughgate.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It may have measured about 104 acres (0.42 km2), divided into 4 *raths* or eight *oxgangs*, the area that eight oxen were said to be able to plough in one year.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the fourteenth century most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, who were usually known as husbandmen or bonders.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The average amount of land used by a husbandman in Scotland, known as a husbandland, was 26 acres, or 2 oxgangs.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They would also have had a share of hay meadow and common pasture.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Below the husbandmen, lesser landholders and free tenants, were the cottars, who often shared rights to common pasture, occupied small portions of land and participated in joint farming as hired labour.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Farms also might have grassmen, who had rights only to grazing.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Pasture was often accessed by shieling-grounds, with shelters made of stone or turf, used for the grazing of cattle in summer.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These would often be distant from the main settlements in the Lowlands, but might be relatively close in the more remote Highlands.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs, were a ridge and furrow pattern, similar to that used in parts of England, with alternating "runs" (furrows) and "rigs" (ridges).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land, helping to offset some of the problems of extreme weather conditions.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective on heavy soils and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were usually pulled by a team of eight oxen, which would have taken four men to operate and only covered half an acre a day.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Key crops included kale (for both humans and animals), and hemp and flax for cloth production.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised primarily for meat.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This was followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Towards the end of the period average temperatures began to reduce again, with the cooler and wetter conditions of the Little Ice Age limiting the extent of arable agriculture, particularly in the Highlands.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Within Scotland, Alexander worked to reinforce his authority across a politically unconsolidated Kingdom.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] He eliminated repeated rebellions in Ross and Moray in the north, and in Galloway in the southwest, including the final destruction of the MacWilliam line.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] He extended royal control into regions where his predecessors could only exercise limited influence.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander extended his interventions on the western seaboard, confronting Norse-influenced lords in Argyll and the Hebrides.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] His dealings with England remained central to his rule.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In 1237, he concluded the Treaty of York with Henry III, which settled border issues and defined the Anglo-Scottish border in largely enduring terms.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] His second marriage, to the French noblewoman Marie de Coucy in 1239, aided Scotland's continental connections.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In his later years, Alexander sought to extend his influence in the west, ending in a campaign against Norse possessions in the Hebrides.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] His intentions were cut short when he died on the island of Kerrera in 1249.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] He was succeeded by his seven-year-old son, Alexander.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander II's reign was important in the development of a more unified and territorially defined Scottish kingdom.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander, son of King William the Lion and Ermengarde de Beaumont, was born on 24 August 1198 at Haddington in Lothian.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] He descended directly from Malcolm III, the first of the Canmore line of kings.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] His first marriage, to the Norse noblewoman Ingibjǫrg Finnsdóttir (d. before 1068), produced a son, Donnchad mac Máel Coluim (Duncan II).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The pretenders, the meic Uilleim (MacWilliams), stemmed from Duncan's line.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander descended from Malcolm's second marriage to Margaret of Wessex, an English princess, who produced six sons and two daughters.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Of the sons, three became kings, but only the youngest, David I, had a legitimate heir—Henry, Earl of Huntingdon.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Henry died before his father but left two legitimate sons, Malcolm IV, who died childless, and William the Lion.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] By the time of Alexander's birth, succession by direct descent of the firstborn male, primogeniture, appeared to have been settled.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Even King William's predecessor, his brother Malcolm—a twelve-year-old minor—had succeeded to the throne without difficulty.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Yet William appears to have had doubts about Alexander's eventual succession.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The reasons are unclear, though the instability created by the English succession crisis between Arthur of Brittany and John of England may have influenced his thinking.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Consequently, at a council of nobles on 12 October 1201, he secured their support to recognise the three‑year‑old Alexander as heir.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] This sidelined William's younger brother, Earl David of Huntingdon, who had been heir presumptive since 1165.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Notably absent from the council, David did not acknowledge Alexander as heir until 1205.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Anglo-Scottish relations deteriorated sharply in the spring of 1209.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Talks originally scheduled for Newcastle were instead held at Norham Castle on the English bank of the River Tweed, ending without agreement on 23 April.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] By late July, both William and John, King of England, mustered their armies at Norham, each believing the other had acted provocatively.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] A contemporary Scottish source estimated John's forces, revealing the scale of his intimidating military display.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The treaty that was concluded on 7 August 1209 was highly unfavourable to Scotland.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] So much so that William tried to conceal some of its provisions; it required him to reaffirm his homage to King John for his English lands, to pay 15,000 marks, and to deliver high‑ranking hostages.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander, approaching his eleventh birthday, was compelled to give homage to John, not only for his eventual inheritance of English lands but for his future kingdom—an acknowledgement of John as his overlord.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Its terms also made clear that Margaret and Isabella, William's daughters, were already in John's charge and were to be provided for in a future marriage arrangement with John's two young sons.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The prospective marriages involved various scenarios depending on the sisters' and the brothers' survivability.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The daughters' status was ambiguous; despite being well received at John's court, they were effectively 'quasi-hostages', with no freedom of movement.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Between 1212 and 1214, the sisters are recorded travelling with the royal court, on occasion in the company of the queen, Isabella of Angoulême, and sometimes with Eleanor of Brittany, who was being held similarly.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In January 1211, the twelve-year-old Alexander witnessed the second MacWilliam (Meic Uilleim) rebellion led by Guthred, the son of Domnall (Donald), the original dissenter.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Although his forces fragmented by the autumn, Guthred himself evaded capture.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] As the rebellion entered its second year, William struggled to contain the uprising, perhaps raising fears regarding Alexander's succession.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] This ongoing instability and William's apparent inability to resolve it were likely the reasons for his need for John's assistance.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In response, John's harsh terms led to the humiliating treaty of 8 February 1212, which significantly strengthened his dominance over the Scottish king.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The agreement required that Alexander would marry only at John's discretion; it also stated that both William and Alexander had acknowledged John and his heir, Henry, as their overlords.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] William had thus conceded to John the right of marriage provision for three of his four legitimate children.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] While the treaty omitted specific mention of John's daughter, Joan, it may have been understood that she would eventually be Alexander's wife.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] As required in the ratified treaty, Alexander travelled to London and was knighted along with thirteen Scottish nobles at Clerkenwell Priory on 4 March 1212.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander returned to Scotland with an escort of John's mercenaries to join the hunt for Guthred MacWilliam.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Ultimately, the rebellion ended when Guthred was betrayed by his own followers and delivered to Alexander at Kincardine Castle, where he was executed.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] By early 1213, Alexander had been introduced into royal government, witnessing charters and attending council meetings.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In the summer of 1214, the ageing and increasingly infirm King William travelled north to secure the loyalty of Jón, Earl of Caithness, taking the earl's daughter as a hostage.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] His return south from Elgin was both slow and arduous, and by early September, he was unable to travel beyond Stirling Castle.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Before William died on 4 December, the kingdom's leading nobles reaffirmed Alexander as heir.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The next day, accompanied by seven earls and Bishop Malveisin of St Andrews, Alexander proceeded to Scone, where he was inaugurated.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] William's body, escorted by senior clergy and the queen, was taken to Perth, only a short distance from Scone, where on 8 December, Alexander met the cortage.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The procession continued to Arbroath Abbey, where William was buried before the high altar on 10 December.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] For Alexander, just a few months past his sixteenth birthday, a minority kingship was not considered.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] He immediately summoned a great court at Edinburgh to take oaths of fealty and to reconfirm his father's principal officers in their roles.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Although his realm nominally stretched from the Pentland Firth to the Solway Firth, he inherited a loosely integrated kingdom in which effective royal authority was strongest in the southeast but weak elsewhere.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The western and northern seaboards bordered the Norwegian king's island dominions from Man to Shetland, where powerful regional lords operated with considerable autonomy.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Against this backdrop, discontent at Alexander's accession encouraged the MacWilliam line to revive its claim to the throne.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Máel Coluim mac Donnchada (Malcolm III) and his first wife, Ingibjǫrg, widow of Earl Thorfinn of Orkney, had at least two sons: Donnchad mac Máel Coluim (Duncan II) and Domnall (Donald).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Little is known of this Donald, who died in 1085.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The deaths of Malcolm III, his eldest son Edward of the second marriage, and Queen Margaret, all within days in November 1093, left the Scottish throne vacant.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Duncan, long absent in England, initially as a hostage, was bypassed in favour of Malcolm's brother Donald III.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] With support from William Rufus, Duncan invaded, briefly ruled, but alienated his followers by relying on English and Norman retainers.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Donald, aided by Edmund, Margaret's eldest surviving son, took the throne following Duncan's murder.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Edgar, another of Margaret's sons, then seized the crown, executed Donald, and exiled Edmund.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Duncan II's son, William fitz Duncan, was excluded from the succession due to his minority, though primogeniture would have favoured him.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] He was also described as Willelmus nepos principis—William, nephew of the prince (i.e.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] David I); on other occasions, Willelmus nepos regis—William, nephew of the king.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Before marrying Alice de Rumelli, he fathered Domnall mac Uilleim (Donald MacWilliam) with an unknown Gaelic woman.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Domnall became the first MacWilliam rebel.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The crown passed through Margaret's sons to David I in 1124.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] William fitz Duncan, now an adult, was likely recognised as David's heir under Tánaiste principles.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Yet, he remained loyal even after David's son, Henry, was styled Rex Designatus around 1141.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Henry's death led to the reigns of Malcolm IV (1153) and William I (1165).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The first meic Uilleim rising emerged by 1179, during William's reign and ended with the death of Donald MacWilliam in 1187.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] By then, the MacWilliams held significant support in Ross, Moray, and Ireland, and by 1187, some magnates considered replacing William I with a MacWilliam claimant.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander II was twelve when the second uprising began in 1211, led by Donald's son Guthred.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Shortly after Alexander's accession, Donald Bán and Kenneth MacHeth launched another rebellion in 1215.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] This was swiftly quashed by the Ross leader Fercher mac an tSacairt (Farquhar MacTaggart).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] On 15 June 1215, MacTaggart presented the rebels' severed heads to the King.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] This intervention demonstrated the effectiveness of the security measures implemented by King William, including the establishment of strategic lordships and castles from Inverness to Sutherland.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] These defenses, combined with the 1214 agreement with Jón, Earl of Caithness, largely stabilized the region.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The final MacWilliam rebellion erupted in 1228, when Gillescop burned Abertarff Castle and killed its governor before advancing on Inverness.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander II appointed William Comyn, Earl of Buchan, to end the revolt.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Gillescop and his sons were killed by 1229/30.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The line ended in the winter of 1230 with the execution of Gillescop's infant daughter at Forfar, the last known member of the MacWilliam line.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In early spring 1215, Alexander received representatives from disaffected English barons, including Eustace de Vescy, his brother‑in‑law with lands in Fife and Lothian, and Saher de Quincy, Earl of Winchester.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Around this time, Eustace de Vescy and Robert de Ros—both married to Alexander's illegitimate sisters—renounced loyalty to King John, as did most northern barons.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The MacWilliam rebellion remained unresolved when civil war erupted in England in early May.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander, an English baron through his Tynedale holdings, adopted a cautious stance, weighing gains from either faction.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] A truce was arranged before the end of May.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] On 15 June, the day Alexander received the rebels’ heads, John sealed the Articles that became the Magna Carta.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Clause 59 addressed grievances concerning Alexander's sisters and hostages held since the 1209 Norham treaty.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] On 7 July, Alexander sent Bishop William de Malveisin of St Andrews and five laymen to John's court to pursue the issues raised in Clause 59.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] They met John at Oxford in mid‑July; although the hostages were likely released, no further progress followed.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] On 5 September, Innocent III's commissioners excommunicated leading rebels and placed their lands under interdict.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Fighting resumed, and John, backed by the Pope, retracted support for the Magna Carta, nullifying Alexander's gains.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The barons, seeking his support, offered him Cumberland, Westmorland, and Northumberland—territories long sought by his father.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] With his interests lost, Alexander crossed the Tweed on 19 October to blockade Norham Castle.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] After forty days the siege was abandoned.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] With winter approaching, he moved south to Newcastle, bypassed its castle, and razed the town.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Provoked, John assembled Brabantian mercenaries and launched a swift winter campaign.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] By 4 January 1216, he reached York and captured several northern castles by 10 January.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] He progressed rapidly, causing the northern barons to flee into Scotland.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] There, they met Alexander at Melrose on 11 January and gave homage and pledges.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] By 15 January, John had taken Berwick and its castle, ravaged Lothian, destroyed Dunbar, Haddington, and Roxburgh.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Returning to Berwick, he razed the town before retreating across the border by 25 January.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] His retreat was likely prompted by Alexander's army assembling near Edinburgh.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] John had failed to dislodge Alexander—mocked as the little red fox—or to force him to abandon the barons.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander pursued him to Swaledale, then returned via the Stainmore pass across the Pennines toward Carlisle, but did not attempt entry.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] His army moved toward the Solway fords, where some Scots, apparently against orders, pillaged Holme Cultram Abbey, a Melrose colony—an act not repeated in his summer campaign.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] On 20 May 1216, papal legate Guala Bicchieri arrived to support John.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The next day, Prince Louis of France landed in Kent at the barons’ invitation.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] By the end of the month, Bicchieri had excommunicated Louis and his allies.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Louis’ arrival coincided with Alexander's resumption of campaigning by returning to the siege of Carlisle in July.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The town fell on 8 August, the castle by December.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Soon after, Alexander left Carlisle to rendezvous with Louis.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Crossing the Pennines, they briefly clashed with the holders of Bernard Castle before continuing south.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Details of their rapid march are unknown, other than passing near Lincoln, where allied barons were besieging the castle.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] After passing close to London, they joined Louis at Canterbury shortly after 8 September and travelled to Dover, where Louis’ forces were sieging the castle.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] There, Alexander paid homage to Louis, perhaps for Lothian and the northern counties.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander left for the north around early October.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Meanwhile, John prepared measures to block his escape.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] On 19 October, Alexander's forces broke through; however, that same day, John died of dysentery, a pivotal event that shifted the war.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Many rebel barons now made peace with John's heir, Henry III.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In November 1216, Bicchieri placed Scotland under interdict.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In September, Louis made peace with Henry and returned to France.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In December 1217 at Berwick, Alexander agreed to surrender Carlisle in exchange for absolution.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Henry received him at Northampton around 19 December, accepting his submission and homage for Tynedale and Huntingdon.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The removal of papal sanctions on Scotland began in early 1218.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The amity between the Scottish and English crowns began to unravel in 1232 with the fall of Alexander's powerful brother-in-law, Hubert de Burgh.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Henry readily agreed to the marriage of Alexander's youngest sister, Margaret (sometimes known as Marjory), to Gilbert the Marshall in 1235—this was the Margaret that Henry himself had agreed to marry in 1231.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Following the marriage, Gilbert left Henry's court, seldom to return.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In 1234, Alexander sought full implementation of the English requirements of the 1209 treaty.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] This prompted Henry to remind the papacy of English claims of overlordship and the contents of the treaties of 1174 and 1209/1212.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Pope Gregory IX responded early in 1235, upheld Henry's claim, and directed Alexander to pay homage to the English king as his overlord.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander ignored this and returned to the unresolved issues over the three northern shires and the breaches of the 1209 and 1231 agreements regarding the marriage arrangements for his eldest and youngest sisters.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] A meeting of the joint courts held at Newcastle in September 1236 was fruitless, heightening Henry's fears of a Scottish attack in northern England.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Otto de Tonengo, the pope's legate, brought the kings together at York in September 1237, and a treaty was quickly finalised.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander waived any demand for repayment of the 15,000 marks previously paid by his father, King William, to King John of England, which were unfulfilled agreements.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] As well as that, all prior matrimonial arrangements between the English and Scottish royal families—specifically, those concerning Henry, his brother Richard, Margaret, Isabella, and Marjory—were set aside.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander was provided with lordships in Cumberland and Northumberland worth £200 annually—comparable to a small barony—although this wasn't implemented until 1242.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] However, these did come with far-reaching privileges, allowing them to function almost as autonomous entities outside English law.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In return, Alexander set aside all claims over the northern counties, but crucially, claims of overlordship had been dropped.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] With the ambiguity of the Northern counties now settled, the position of the border between the two countries could now be agreed upon—this may have been achieved in 1249, leaving only small pockets of land in contention.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] This laid the foundation of an unprecedented, uninterrupted peace that began in 1217 and lasted beyond Alexander's son's death in 1286, to 1296.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Queen Joan died on 4 March 1238, and Alexander remarried in May 1239 to Marie de Coucy, daughter of a prominent French noble.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The marriage sparked English concerns about a potential alliance between Alexander and Louis IX, bringing the kingdoms to the edge of war in 1244.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The situation was resolved when both kings met at Newcastle on 14 August 1244.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The resulting treaty outlined Alexander's pledge to refrain from future hostilities against Henry, except in defence of Scottish interests.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Additionally, it was agreed that Alexander's son, also named Alexander, would eventually marry Henry's first-born daughter, Margaret.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander inherited an amorphous, loosely held kingdom in which his authority barely extended beyond its southeastern core.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The semi-independent brothers Alan and Thomas of Galloway were deploying their substantial land and naval forces against the Kingdom of Man and the Isles.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander probably approved of this, as it promised the combined advantages of suppressing the MacWilliam support within the Irish Sea zone while expanding his influence over the Firth of Clyde region—a prerequisite for dominating southwest Argyll and the southern isles.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Between 1214 and 1230 Alexander continued his policy of de-stabilising the Manx kingdom by his continued approval of Alan, lord of Galloway and also Ferchar mac an t-saggairt, now earl of Ross, in their Manx activities.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alan and Ferchar had their separate agendas but never seemed to have been at odds with one another, and both retained Alexander's favour.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In early 1221, Alexander was at Inverness to put down an uprising by Donald MacNeil, of whom nothing else is known.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] By April, Alexander had returned south to Perth, possibly concluding his campaign.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] That he was able to attend his wedding in York in June, being accompanied by his northern commander, William Comyn, Earl of Buchan, suggests that it had been.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In the summer months of 1221 and 1222, Alexander, together with Alan and Thomas of Galloway, called out the levies of Lothian and Galloway and sailed against Ruaidhri mac Raonaill, lord of Kintyre, and seized control of Cowal, Knapdale and Kintyre at this time.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The 1222 campaign was brief, leading to Ruaidhri's expulsion from his remaining mainland territories.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] His younger brother Domhnall subsequently received the lordship after submitting to Alexander.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In what was likely the fourth week of September 1222, Alexander began his safe-conduct journey of pilgrimage to Canterbury.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] On reaching only as far as Jedburgh, he was met with the news that his bishop, Adam of Caithness, had been burned alive in his home at Halkirk by some of his parishioners on 11 September.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Adam had been one of only four Scottish bishops who attended the fourth Lateran Council in Rome that opened on 11 November 1215, and it was at this council that changes involving tiend payments were agreed.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] His application of the Lateran Council's canons was responsible for the free peasant farmers' revolt against the church in Caithness and the bishop's death.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Jón, Earl of Caithness and Jarl of Orkney, did not intervene to prevent the murder.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander immediately marched an army, gathered as he travelled, north to Caithness, where he brutally maimed those responsible and confiscated a significant portion of Jón's lands.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Norwegian sovereignty over Jón's Orkney jarldom was reasserted after his father died in 1206.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In contrast, Scottish authority had declined in Caithness while Alexander focused on events in England.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] This incident had the two-fold effect of reaffirming Alexander's primacy over Jón's Caithness and communicating this firmly to Norway.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] By around 1225, the western seaboard saw further consolidation as the meic Dubhghaills (MacDougalls), descendants of Somerled, King of the Isles, reappeared in records, after a gap of fifty years, as a dominant force.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] This was marked by the emergence of Donnchadh mac Dubhghaill (Duncan MacDougall) as the lord of Lorn and a prominent ally of King Alexander.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alan, Lord of Galloway—one of Alexander's most formidable magnates—succeeded to lordships in Scotland and England, and the office of Constable of Scotland following his father Roland's death in 1200.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] His position was unique; while holding Cunningham and Lauderdale as a feudal vassal, his Galloway lordship remained a quasi-independent territory with its own laws and conventions.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alan was a significant figure in both kingdoms.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] He descended from Henry I of England and was the son‑in‑law of Alexander's uncle, Earl David of Huntingdon.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alan's influence derived less from these considerations than from his extensive cross‑border estates and his powerful military capability—operating by land and sea and drawn upon by kings on both sides of the border.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Though Alan assisted King John when their ambitions aligned, he remained Alexander's chief lieutenant during the Anglo-Scottish war of 1215–17, leading the occupation of Cumberland and Westmorland.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Nevertheless, his independent political agenda and frequent absence from court caused some uncertainty.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] By the mid-1220s, Alan's interference in the Manx dynastic struggle between half-brothers, Ragnvald and Olaf, contributed to some of the destabilisation in the Irish Sea zone.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] By marrying his illegitimate son, Tomás, to Ragnvald's daughter, Alan sought to secure the Manx throne for Tomás.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] News of considerable unrest in Man and the Hebrides reached King Hákon of Norway in 1229, prompted in part by Alan's renewed hostilities in the region.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Hákon dispatched a force to reassert his authority, but it achieved little.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In 1230–31, Alan's continued operations drew Hákon back into the conflict when his galleys re‑entered the Isles, creating a major crisis for Alexander.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The MacDougall kindred (the meic Dubhghaill), whom Alexander had promoted as one of his proxies in the Isles from 1221, were also following a personal agenda.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Following Alan's death in 1234, Alexander blocked Alan's illegitimate son Tomás's claim to a unified lordship, insisting instead on the feudal partition of Galloway among Alan's legitimate daughters.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] This sparked a fierce rebellion led by Tomás in 1235 and supported by local lords eager to preserve Galloway's autonomy.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In early July 1235, Alexander took his army into Galloway, but resistance was fierce; the Scottish host was nearly defeated in an ambush near Kenmore (present day *Kenmure*), saved only by the opportune arrival of Ferchar, Earl of Ross, who defeated the rebels.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander's initial attempt to hold the region under Walter Comyn failed when Tomás returned with Irish reinforcements.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In April 1236, a second army led by the Earl of Dunbar—supported by Alan of Galloway's close friend, Gilbert, bishop of Whithorn—finally forced the rebels to surrender.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Tomás was to spend the remainder of his life in captivity, initially at Edinburgh Castle and then at Barnard Castle under the supervision of his half-sister, Dervorguilla.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The rebellion's collapse ensured Galloway's full absorption into Alexander's feudal order.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The king divided the lordship among Alan's three legitimate daughters—Helen, Dervorguilla, and Christiana—and their Anglo-Norman spouses.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Eóghan mac Donnchadh meic Dubhghaill (*Ewan, son of Duncan, of the MacDougall kindred*) succeeded as lord of Argyll (Lorn) after his father's death, which may have been in 1237.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] His mainland lordship of Argyll was as a vassal of Alexander II, while his islands were held of his Norwegian overlord, Hákon IV.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] To the north, his kinsman Dubhghaill mac Ruaidhrí (Dougall, son of Roderic) possessed the lordship of Garmoran in the same manner.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Although Alexander had remained active in the west, his final settlement with Henry III in 1244 allowed him to plan for fuller integration of the western seaboard lordships.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] By 1244, Alexander had consolidated the mainland territories south of Argyll into the kingdom.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] That year, and over the next five, he pressed his offer to buy the isles from Hákon with 'refined silver'.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] From spring 1248, both Ewan and Dougall were in Bergen to press their claims to the vacant kingship of the Isles, following the death of Ruaidhrí mac Raghnaill.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Ewan and Dougall remained there into the autumn, when Hákon finally came down in Ewan's favour.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The king of Man had drowned in early 1249; as a temporary expedient, Hákon quickly made Ewan ruler of Man in addition to his Isles kingdom.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Ewan's overt alignment with Norway, including his homage given to Hákon, and Hákon's empowerment of Ewan, a Scottish baron, made the situation intolerable for Alexander.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] In February 1249, Alexander called his principal advisors together in Stirling.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] It may have been at this meeting, or at one held soon after, that a decision was taken to launch a joint land-and-sea action against Ewan and his lordship.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Logistically, this required mustering levies, certainly from Angus but likely from other regions, and a fleet ready for a summer campaign.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] During Lent 1248 (4 March to 16 April), Alexander was reported as being unwell.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] It is not known whether this period of ill health continued into 1249; however, around the end of the first week of July, Alexander's fleet reached Kerrera, and the king was already gravely ill.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] He was carried ashore onto the small island, where on 8 July 1249, at about three o'clock in the afternoon, Alexander died.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] The king's death brought the campaign to a stop.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] His nobles immediately returned to the east for the inauguration of the new king, Alexander III.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-ii-of-scotland] Alexander's body was taken back to the mainland and then to Melrose Abbey, where he was buried.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Alexander was born at Roxburgh, the only son of Alexander II by his second wife, Marie de Coucy.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] His father died on 6 July 1249 and he became king at the age of seven, inaugurated at Scone on 13 July 1249.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] The years of his minority featured an embittered struggle for the control of affairs between two rival parties, the one led by Walter Comyn, Earl of Menteith, the other by Alan Durward, Justiciar of Scotia.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] The former dominated the early years of Alexander's reign.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] At the marriage of Alexander to Margaret of England in 1251, Henry III of England seized the opportunity to demand homage from his son-in-law for the Scottish kingdom, but Alexander did not comply.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] In 1255 an interview between the English and Scottish kings at Kelso led to Menteith and his party losing to Durward's party.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] However, although disgraced, they still retained great influence, and two years later, seizing the person of the King, they compelled their rivals to consent to the establishment of a regency representative of both parties.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] On attaining his majority at the age of 21 in 1262, Alexander declared his intention to resume the projects on the Western Isles which the death of his father thirteen years before had cut short.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] He laid a formal claim before King Haakon IV of Norway.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Haakon rejected the claim, and in the following year, responded with a formidable invasion.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Sailing around the west coast of Scotland, he halted off the Isle of Arran, and negotiations commenced.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Alexander artfully prolonged the talks until the autumn storms began.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] At length Haakon, weary of delay, attacked, only to encounter a terrific storm which greatly damaged his ships.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] The Battle of Largs on 2 October 1263 proved indecisive, but even so, Haakon's position was hopeless.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Baffled, he turned homewards, but died in Orkney on 15 December 1263.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] The Isles now lay at Alexander's feet, and in 1266 Haakon's successor, his son Magnus the Lawmender, concluded the Treaty of Perth, by which he ceded the Isle of Man and the Western Isles to Scotland in return for monetary payments.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Norway retained Orkney and Shetland until 1469, when they became a dowry for James III's bride, Margaret of Denmark.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Alexander had married Margaret of England, daughter of King Henry III of England and Eleanor of Provence, on 26 December 1251, when he was ten years old and she was eleven.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] David (20 March 1272 – June 1281 Stirling Castle), buried in Dunfermline Abbey.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Towards the end of Alexander's reign, the death of all three of his children within a few years made the question of the succession one of pressing importance.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] In 1284, he induced the Estates to recognise as his heir presumptive his granddaughter, Margaret, Maid of Norway.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] The need for a male heir led him to contract a second marriage to Yolande of Dreux on 1 November 1285.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Alexander died in a fall from his horse while riding in the dark to visit the Queen at Kinghorn in Fife on 19 March 1286 because it was her birthday the next day.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] He had spent the evening at Edinburgh Castle celebrating his second marriage and overseeing a meeting with royal advisers.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] He was cautioned against making the journey to Fife because of weather conditions but crossed the River Forth from Dalmeny to Inverkeithing anyway.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] On arriving in Inverkeithing, he insisted on not stopping for the night, despite the pleas of the nobles accompanying him and one of the burgesses of the town, Alexander Le Saucier.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Le Saucier (who was either linked to the King's kitchen or the master of the local saltpans) must have been known to the King, since his rather blunt warning to the King lacks the usual deference: "My lord, what are you doing out in such weather and darkness?
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] However, Alexander ignored the repeated warnings about travelling in a storm and set off with his retinue and two local guides.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] The king became separated from his party near Kinghorn, and was found dead with a broken neck near the shore the following morning.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] It is assumed that his horse lost its footing in the dark.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] As Alexander left no surviving children, the heir to the throne was his unborn child by Queen Yolande.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] When Yolande's pregnancy ended, probably with a miscarriage, Alexander's three-year-old granddaughter, Margaret, Maid of Norway, became the heir.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Margaret died, still uncrowned, on her way to Scotland in 1290.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] The inauguration of John Balliol as King on 30 November 1292 ended the six years of the Guardians of Scotland governing the land.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] In 1886, a monument to Alexander III was erected at the approximate location of his death in Kinghorn.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] This was, in tradition, an omen of death.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] A similar account is given in Walter Bower's *Scotichronicon*, a figure that "seemed to glide like a ghost rather than walk on feet" supposedly appeared amidst a group performing Scottish sword dances.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Alexander III has been depicted in historical novels.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In present usage, "anointing" is typically used for ceremonial blessings such as the coronation of European monarchs.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] This continues an earlier Hebrew practice most famously observed in the anointings of Aaron as high priest and both Saul and David by the prophet Samuel.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The concept is important to the figure of the Messiah or the Christ (Hebrew and Greek for "The Anointed One") who appear prominently in Jewish and Christian theology and eschatology.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Anointing—particularly the anointing of the sick—may also be known as **unction**; the anointing of the dying as part of last rites in the Catholic church is sometimes specified as "extreme unction".
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The present verb derives from the now obsolete adjective *anoint*, equivalent to *anointed*.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The adjective is first attested in 1303, derived from Old French *enoint*, the past participle of *enoindre*, from Latin *inung*(*u*)*ere*, an intensified form of *ung*(*u*)*ere* 'to anoint'.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The oil used in a ceremonial anointment may be called "chrism", from Greek χρῖσμα (*khrîsma*) 'anointing'.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Anointing served and serves three distinct purposes: it is regarded as a means of health and comfort, as a token of honor, and as a symbol of consecration.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] It seems probable that its sanative purposes were enjoyed before it became an object of ceremonial religion, but the custom appears to predate written history and the archaeological record, and its genesis is impossible to determine with certainty.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Used in conjunction with bathing, anointment with oil closes pores.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] It was regarded as counteracting the influence of the sun, reducing sweating.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Aromatic oils naturally masked body and other offensive odors.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Applications of oils and fats are also used as traditional medicines.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The Bible records olive oil being applied to the sick and poured into wounds.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Known sources date from times when anointment already served a religious function; therefore, anointing was also used to combat the malicious influence of demons in Persia, Armenia, and Greece.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Anointing was also understood to "seal in" goodness and resist corruption, probably via analogy with the use of a top layer of oil to preserve wine in ancient amphoras, its spoiling usually being credited to demonic influence.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] For sanitary and religious reasons, the bodies of the dead are sometimes anointed.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In medieval and early modern Christianity, the practice was particularly associated with protection against vampires and ghouls who might otherwise take possession of the corpse.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Anointing guests with oil as a mark of hospitality and token of honor is recorded in Egypt, Greece, and Rome, as well as in the Hebrew scriptures.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] It was a common custom among the ancient Hebrews and continued among the Arabs into the 20th century.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In the sympathetic magic common to prehistoric and primitive religions, the fat of sacrificial animals and persons is often reckoned as a powerful charm, second to blood as the vehicle and seat of life.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] East African Arabs traditionally anointed themselves with lion's fat to gain courage and provoke fear in other animals.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Australian Aborigines would rub themselves with a human victim's caul fat to gain his powers.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In religions like Christianity where animal sacrifice is no longer practiced, it is common to consecrate the oil in a special ceremony.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] According to scholars belonging to the early part of the twentieth century (Wilhelm Spiegelberg, Bonnet, Cothenet, Kutsch, Martin-Pardey) officials of ancient Egypt were anointed as part of a ceremony that installed them into office.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Anointment of the corpse with scented oils was however a well attested practice as an important part of mummification.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In Indian religion, late Vedic rituals developed involving the anointing of government officials, worshippers, and idols.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The practice spread to Indian Buddhists.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In modern Hinduism and Jainism, anointment is common, although the practice typically employs water or yoghurt, milk, or (particularly) butter from the holy cow, rather than oil.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Many devotees are anointed as an act of consecration or blessing at every stage of life, with rituals accompanying birthing, educational enrollments, religious initiations, and death.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] New buildings, houses, and ritual instruments are anointed, and some idols are anointed daily.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Particular care is taken in such rituals to the *direction* of the smearing.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] People are anointed from head to foot, downwards.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The water may derive from one of the holy rivers or be scented with saffron, turmeric, or flower infusions; the waste water produced when cleaning certain idols or when writing certain verses of scripture may also be used.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Ointments may include ashes, clay, powdered sandalwood, or herbal pastes.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Buddhist practices of anointing are largely derived from Indian practices but tend to be less elaborate and more ritualized.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Buddhists may sprinkle assembled practitioners with water or mark idols of Buddha or the Bodhisattvas with cow or yak butter.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Flower-scented water is also used, as are ink-water and "saffron water" stained yellow using saffron or turmeric.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In antiquity, use of a holy anointing oil was significant in the Hebrews' consecration of priests, the Kohen Gadol (High Priest), and the sacred vessels.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Prophets and the Israelite kings were anointed as well, the kings from a horn.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Anointment by the chrism prepared according to the ceremony described in the Book of Exodus was considered to impart the "Spirit of the Lord".
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] It was performed by Samuel in place of a coronation of both Saul and David.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The practice was not always observed and seems to have been essential only at the consecration of a new line or dynasty.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Because of its importance, the High Priest and the king were sometimes called "the Anointed One".
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The term—מָשִׁיחַ, *Mashiaẖ*—gave rise to the prophesied figure of the Messiah (*q.v.*) and a long history of claimants.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The expression "anoint the shield" which occurs in Isaiah is a related or poetic usage, referring to the practice of rubbing oil on the leather of the shield to keep it supple and fit for war.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The practice of anointing a shield predates the anointing of other objects in that the "smearing" (Hebrew *mashiach*) of the shield renewed the leather covering on a wooden shield.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] A victorious soldier was elevated on his shield by his comrades after a battle or upon his selection as a new king.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Christianity developed from the association of Jesus of Nazareth with the Jewish prophecies of an "Anointed One".
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] His epithet "Christ" is a form of the Greek equivalent of the Hebrew title.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] He was not anointed by the High Priest in accordance with the ceremony described in Exodus, but he was considered to have been anointed by the Holy Spirit during his baptism.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] A literal anointing of Jesus also occurs when he was lavishly oiled by Mary of Bethany.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Performed out of affection, the anointment is said by Jesus to have been preparation for his burial.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In the New Testament, John describes "anointing from the Holy One" and "from Him abides in you".
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Both this spiritual anointment and literal anointment with oil are usually associated with the Holy Spirit.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Eastern Orthodox churches in particular attach great importance to the oil said to have been originally blessed by the Twelve Apostles.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The practice of "chrismation" (baptism with oil) appears to have developed in the early church during the later 2nd century as a symbol of Christ, rebirth, and inspiration.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The earliest surviving account of such an act seems to be the letter written "To Autolycus" by Theophilus, bishop of Antioch.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In it, he calls the act "sweet and useful", punning on *khristós* (Ancient Greek: χριστóς, "anointed") and *khrēstós* (χρηστóς, "useful").
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Origen opines that "all of us may be baptized in those visible waters and in a visible anointing, in accordance with the form handed down to the churches".
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Anointing was particularly important among the Gnostics.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Many early apocryphal and Gnostic texts state that John the Baptist's baptism by water was incomplete and that anointment with oil is a necessary part of the baptismal process.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In the Acts of Thomas, the anointing is the beginning of the baptismal ritual and essential to becoming a Christian, as it says God knows his own children by his seal and that the seal is received through the oil.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Many such chrismations are described in detail through the work.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In medieval and early modern Christianity, the oil from the lamps burnt before the altar of a church was felt to have particular sanctity.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] New churches and altars were anointed at their four corners during their dedication, as were tombs, gongs, and some other ritual instruments and utensils.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The Roman Catholic, Anglican and Lutheran Churches bless three types of holy oils for anointing: "Oil of the Catechumens" (abbreviated OS, from the Latin *oleum sanctum*, meaning holy oil), "Oil of the Infirm" (OI), and "Sacred Chrism" (SC).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The first two are said to be blessed, while the chrism is consecrated.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The Oil of Catechumens is used to people immediately before baptism, whether they are infants or adult catechumens.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In the early church converts seeking baptism, known as "catechumens", underwent a period of formation known as catechumenate, and during that period of instruction received one or more anointings with the oil of cathecumens for the purpose of expelling evil spirits.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In the later form, priests, like bishops, are anointed with chrism, the hands of a priest, the head of a bishop.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] (In the older form, a bishop's hands, as well as the head, are anointed with chrism.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The traditional Roman Pontifical also has a rite of coronation of kings and queens including anointing with the Oil of Catechumens.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In some countries, as in France, the oil used in that rite was chrism.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Oil of the Infirm is used for administration of the sacrament of anointing of the sick, the ritual treatment of the sick and infirm through what was usually called Extreme Unction in Western Christianity from the late 12th to the late 20th century.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Sacred Chrism is used in the sacraments of baptism, confirmation, and holy orders.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] It is also used in the dedication of new churches, new altars, and in the consecration of new patens and chalices for use in Mass.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In the case of the sacrament of baptism, the subject receives two distinct unctions: one with the oil of catechumens, prior to being baptized, and then, after baptism with water is performed, the subject receives an unction with chrism.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In the case of the sacrament of confirmation, anointing with chrism is the essential part of the rite.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Any bishop may consecrate the holy oils.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] They normally do so every Holy Thursday at a special "Chrism Mass".
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In the Eastern Orthodox and Eastern Catholic churches, confirmation is known as chrismation.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The Mystery of Chrismation is performed immediately after the Mystery of Baptism as part of a single ceremony.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The ritual employs the sacred *myron* (μύρον, "chrism"), which is said to contain a remnant of oil blessed by the Twelve Apostles.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In order to maintain the apostolic blessing unbroken, the container is never completely emptied but it is refilled as needed, usually at a ceremony held on Holy Thursday at the Patriarchate of Constantinople or the patriarchal cathedrals of the autocephalous churches.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] At the Patriarchate of Constantinople, the process is under the care of the *Archontes Myrepsoi*, lay officials of the patriarchate.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Various members of the clergy may also participate in the preparation, but the consecration itself is always performed by the patriarch or a bishop deputed by him for that purpose.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The new *myron* contains olive oil, myrrh, and numerous spices and perfumes.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] This *myron* is normally kept on the Holy Table or on the Table of Oblation.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] During chrismation, the "newly illuminate" person is anointed by using the *myron* to make the sign of the cross on the forehead, eyes, nostrils, lips, both ears, breast, hands, and feet.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The priest uses a special brush for this purpose.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Prior to the 20th century, the *myron* was also used for the anointing of Orthodox monarchs.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The oil that is used to anoint the catechumens before baptism is simple olive oil which is blessed by the priest immediately before he pours it into the baptismal font.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Then, using his fingers, he takes some of the blessed oil floating on the surface of the baptismal water and anoints the catechumen on the forehead, breast, shoulders, ears, hands, and feet.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] He then immediately baptizes the catechumen with threefold immersion in the name of the Trinity.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Anointing of the sick is called the "Sacred Mystery of Unction".
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The practice is used for spiritual ailments as well as physical ones, and the faithful may request unction any number of times at will.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In some churches, it is normal for all of the faithful to receive unction during a service on Holy Wednesday of Holy Week.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The holy oil used at unction is not stored in the church like the *myron*, but consecrated anew for each individual service.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] When an Orthodox Christian dies, if he has received the Mystery of Unction and some of the consecrated oil remains, it is poured over his body just before burial.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In the Armenian Church, crosses are traditionally not considered holy until they have been anointed and prayed over, thus introducing the Holy Spirit into them.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The same ritual was formerly observed in the other Orthodox churches.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Owing to their particular focus upon the action of the Holy Spirit, Pentecostal churches sometimes continue to employ anointing for consecration and ordination of pastors and elders, as well as for healing the sick.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The Pentecostal expression "the anointing breaks the yoke" derives from a passage in Isaiah which discusses the power given the prophet Hezekiah by the Holy Spirit over the tyrant Sennacherib.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints practice anointing with pure, consecrated olive oil in two ways: 1) as a priesthood ordinance in preparation for the administration of a priesthood blessing, and 2) in conjunction with washing as part of the endowment.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The Doctrine and Covenants contains numerous references to anointing and administration to the sick by those with authority to perform the laying on of hands.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] On 21 January 1836, Joseph Smith instituted anointing during the rites of sanctification and consecration preparatory to the rites practiced in the Kirtland Temple.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The anointing would prepare church members to receive the endowment of "power from on high" promised in an earlier 1831 revelation.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] At the present time, any holder of the Melchizedek priesthood may anoint the head of an individual by the laying on of hands.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Olive oil must be used if available, and it must have been consecrated earlier in a short ordinance that any holder of the Melchizedek priesthood may perform.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In addition to its use for the Israelite kingship, anointing has been an important ritual in Christian rites of Coronation, especially in Europe.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Later French legend held that a vial of oil, the Holy Ampulla, descended from Heaven to anoint Clovis I as the king of the Franks following his conversion to Christianity in 493.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The Visigoth Wamba is the earliest Catholic king known to have been anointed, although the practice apparently preceded him in Spain.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The ceremony, which closely followed the rite described by the Old Testament., was performed in 672 by Quiricus, the archbishop of Toledo; It was apparently copied a year later when Flavius Paulus defected and joined the Septimanian rebels he had been tasked with quieting.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The rite epitomized the Catholic Church's sanctioning the monarch's rule; it was notably employed by usurpers such as Pepin, whose dynasty replaced the Merovingians in 751.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] While it might be argued that the practice subordinated the king to the church, in practice the sacral anointing of kings was seen as elevating the king to priestly or even saintly status.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Lupoi argues that this set in motion the conflicting claims that developed into the Investiture Crisis.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] At the same time, royal unction recontextualized the elections and popular acclamations still legally responsible for the elevation of new rulers.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] They were no longer understood as autonomous authorities but merely agents in service of God's will.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Napoleon was reportedly anointed in the presence of the Pope at his coronation.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In Eastern Orthodoxy, the anointing of a new king is considered a Sacred Mystery.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The act is believed to empower him—through the grace of the Holy Spirit—with the ability to discharge his divinely appointed duties, particularly his ministry in defending the faith.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The same *myron* used in Chrismation is used for the ceremony.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In Russian Orthodox ceremonial, the anointing took place during the coronation of the tsar towards the end of the service, just before his receipt of Holy Communion.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The sovereign and his consort were escorted to the Holy Doors (Iconostasis) of the cathedral and jointly anointed by the metropolitan.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] Afterwards, the tsar was taken alone through the Holy Doors—an action normally reserved only for priests—and received communion at a small table set next to the Holy Table.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] In the present day, royal unction is less common, being practiced only upon the monarchs of Britain and of Tonga.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The utensils for the practice are sometimes reckoned as regalia, like the ampulla and spoon used in the Kingdom of France and the anointing horns used in Sweden and Norway.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] The Biblical formula is not necessarily followed.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/anointing] For the 1626 coronation of King Charles I of England, the holy oil was made of a concoction of orange, jasmine, distilled roses, distilled cinnamon, and ben oil.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Bek and his elder brother Thomas Bek were members of a family of knights.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Their father was Walter Bek, who held lands at Eresby in Lincolnshire.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Another brother was John Beke, 1st Baron Beke of Eresby, who held the family lands in Eresby.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Walter had married Eve, the niece of Walter de Gray, Archbishop of York.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Bek was born about 1245 and was Walter's third son.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Both Thomas and Antony were educated at Oxford University, where they studied from 1267 to 1270.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Having entered the clergy, Bek received several benefices and soon attracted the attention of the Lord Edward, the heir of King Henry III of England.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] He was Archdeacon of Durham by 1275, as well as precentor of York and held prebends at Lichfield, London, and Wells.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Bek accompanied Edward when the prince went on Crusade in 1270.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] When Edward returned from crusading, he appointed Bek to the office of Keeper of the wardrobe on 21 September 1274, but Bek held the office for only about a month, and was replaced in October with his brother Thomas Bek.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Edward named Bek the constable of the Tower of London in 1275.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] In November 1277 Bek was one of the councillors sent by Edward to negotiate with Llywelyn ap Gruffudd, Prince of Wales.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] The result was the Treaty of Aberconwy which required Llywelyn to give up hostages, pay a large fine, give up claims to some lands and pay homage to King Edward.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Bek was also sent to Aragon to negotiate the marriage of Edward's daughter Eleanor to the heir of Aragon, Alfonso.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Edward I secured Bek's election as bishop of Durham in 1283.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] He was elected on 9 July 1283 and consecrated on 9 January 1284.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] During his consecration, Bek had the remains of Saint William of York moved to a new shrine in York Minster.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Bek was enthroned at Durham Cathedral on 25 December 1285.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Bek was sent to Scotland after the death of King Alexander III of Scotland in 1286, to act on Edward's behalf for Alexander's heir Margaret of Norway, who was bethrothed to Edward's son Prince Edward.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] However, Margaret died soon after this, and Edward was brought in to decide the succession of the Scottish throne.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Bek was employed by King Edward in the negotiations and also served as a spokesman.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] In November 1292, Edward decided in favor of John Balliol, and Bek assisted in the enthronement of Balliol at Scone soon after.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] In 1293, Bek was excommunicated by the Archbishop of York because Bek had allowed the king's officers to arrest two clerks while Bek was in Scotland on a royal mission.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] In response, a legal case was brought against the archbishop in Parliament alleging that because Bek was acting as the king's officer at the time, he wasn't acting as bishop but as earl palatine, and thus the excommunication was actually an affront to the royal dignity.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Before the case could be decided, the archbishop yielded and was fined.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] In 1294 the king sent Bek, along with others, on a diplomatic errand to the German king Adolf of Nassau and the archbishop of Cologne.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] The embassy was attempting to secure allies for Edward's war against King Philip IV of France.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Taking part in Edward's campaigns in Scotland, the bishop received the surrender of King John I of Scotland at Brechin in 1296, and led one division of the English army at the Battle of Falkirk in 1298.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] During the Falkirk campaign, but before the battle itself, a section of the army under Bek captured Dirleton Castle.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] In 1300, soon after his return to England, Bek became involved in a quarrel with Richard de Hoton, Prior of Durham and the cathedral chapter.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Both Hoton and the chapter were attempting to assert their independence from oversight by the bishop.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Bek deposed and excommunicated the prior, and locked the cathedral and the priory up.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Appeals from both sides were made to the king, but the prior had previously secured the support of several of the king's advisors.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Attempts to secure a negotiated settlement failed, and other disputes over lands and rights escalated the dispute.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] At sometime after 1301 the king confiscated the lands of the bishop.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] A settlement in 1303 which restored the bishop's lands, did not settle the dispute between the prior and the bishop.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] In 1304, further charges were brought against the bishop by the prior and the cathedral chapter, including a serious one of imprisoning a royal messenger.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] The issue of the messenger led to the lands of the bishop once more being confiscated in 1305.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] The bishop secured the support of Pope Clement V who named Bek Patriarch of Jerusalem on 26 February 1306.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Further actions against the bishop were stopped by the death of the king in 1307.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Bek conducted the funeral service for King Edward I on 27 October 1307 at Westminster Abbey.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] In September, shortly after the death of Edward I, Edward II restored Bek's lands and rights.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Bek's title of patriarch made him the senior ecclesiastic in England, and it was probably due to that status that he was named the main investigator of the Templars in 1308.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] In 1309, he finally managed to visit the priory at Durham, and the new prior announced that he and the chapter would not institute any more legal proceedings against the bishop stemming from the dispute.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] The bishop died at Eltham Palace near London on 3 March 1311.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] He was buried on 3 May 1311 in Durham Cathedral.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Bek served as an important advisor to King Edward I throughout most of his term as bishop, only losing that status at the end of Edward's reign due to the dispute with the Durham prior.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] His extravagance was legendary, and his retinue was large, and consisted of 140 knights.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Bek was a wealthy man, and his personal estate at his death was valued at 6000 marks.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] He built at Auckland Castle, Somerton Castle in Lincolnshire and elsewhere.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] He also built Durham Castle's Great Hall.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Some efforts were made after the bishop's death to have him canonized, but nothing came of these efforts.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Bek was known for his chastity and bravery also.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Bek's elder brother, Thomas Bek, was Bishop of St David's and a trusted servant of Edward I.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/antony-bek-bishop-of-durham] Two other relations were Thomas Bek, who was Bishop of Lincoln, and Antony Bek, who was Bishop of Norwich.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] When the crown of Scotland became vacant in September 1290 on the death of the seven-year-old Queen Margaret, 13 claimants to the throne came forward.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Those with the most credible claims were John Balliol; Robert de Brus, 5th Lord of Annandale (also spelled "Bruce"); John Hastings, 1st Baron Hastings; and Floris V, Count of Holland.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Fearing civil war, the Guardians of Scotland asked Edward I of England to arbitrate.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Before agreeing, he obtained concessions going some way to revive English overlordship over the Scots.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] A commission of 104 "auditors" was then appointed—24 by Edward himself, acting as president; and the rest by Brus and Balliol, in equal numbers.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] In November 1292, the body decided in favour of John Balliol, whose claim was based on the traditional criterion of primogeniture—inheritance through a line of firstborn sons.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] The decision was accepted by the majority of the powerful in Scotland, and John ruled as King of Scots from then until 1296, when he was succeeded by Robert de Brus, another claimant.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] With the death of King Alexander III in 1286, the crown of Scotland passed to his only surviving descendant, his three-year-old granddaughter Margaret (the Maid of Norway).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] In 1290, the Guardians of Scotland, who had been appointed to govern the realm during the young Queen's minority, drew up the Treaty of Birgham, a marriage contract between Margaret and the five-year-old Edward of Caernarfon, heir apparent to the English throne.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] The treaty, amongst other points, contained the provision that although the issue of this marriage would inherit the crowns of both England and Scotland, the latter kingdom should be "separate, apart and free in itself without subjection to the English Kingdom".
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] The intent was to keep Scotland an independent entity.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Margaret died on 26 September 1290 in Orkney on her way to Scotland, leaving the throne vacant.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] The Guardians called upon her fiancé's father, Edward I of England, to conduct a court in which 104 auditors would choose from among the various claimants of the Scottish throne in a process known as the **Great Cause** (Scottish Gaelic: *An t-Adhbhar Mòr*).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Scotland looked to be headed for civil war.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] To avoid the catastrophe of open warfare between Brus and Balliol, the Guardians and other Scots magnates asked Edward I to intervene.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Edward seized the occasion as an opportunity to gain something he had long desired—legal recognition that the realm of Scotland was held as a feudal dependency to the throne of England.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Alexander III, giving homage to Edward, had chosen his words very carefully: "I become your man for the lands I hold of you in the Kingdom of England for which I owe homage, *saving my Kingdom*" (author's italics).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] In line with this desire, Edward demanded in May 1291 that his claim of feudal overlordship of Scotland be recognised before he would step in and act as arbiter.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] He demanded that the Scots produce evidence to show that he was not the lawful overlord, rather than presenting them with evidence that he was.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] The Scots' reply came that without a king there was no one in the realm responsible enough to possibly make such an admission, and so any assurances given by the Scots were worthless.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Although technically and legally correct by the standards of the time, this reply infuriated Edward so much that he refused to have it entered on the official record of the proceedings.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] The Guardians and the claimants still needed Edward's help, and he did manage to press them into accepting a number of lesser though still important terms.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] The majority of the claimants and the Guardians did eventually step forward to acknowledge Edward as their rightful overlord, even though they could not be taken as speaking for the realm as a whole.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] They also agreed to put Edward in temporary control of the principal royal castles of Scotland, despite the castles in question not being theirs to give away.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] For his part, Edward agreed that he would return control of both kingdom and castles to the successful claimant within two months.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] In the ongoing negotiations between the two countries, the Scots continued to use the Treaty of Birgham as a reference point, indicating that they still wished to see Scotland retain an identity independent from England.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] These concessions obtained, Edward arranged for a court to decide which of the claimants should inherit the throne.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] It consisted of 104 auditors plus Edward himself as president.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Edward chose 24 of the auditors while the two claimants with the strongest cases—Brus and Balliol—were allowed to appoint forty each.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] When Margaret died, there were no close relatives to whom the succession might pass in a smooth and clear manner.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] In addition to these relatives, there were noblemen descended from illegitimate daughters of more recent Scottish kings who also made claims.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] In reality only four of these men had genuine claims to the throne: John Balliol, Robert de Brus, John Hastings, and Floris V (Count of Holland).
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Of these only Brus and Balliol had realistic grounds on which to claim the crown.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] The rest merely wished to have their claims put on the legal record.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] These four all made their claim as being direct legitimate descendants of David I of Scotland who was the grandfather of King William the Lion.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Since William had no living descendants, they made their claim as living descendants of William's brothers and sisters.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Robert de Pinkeney claim was dismissed as it was made through the Donald III of Scotland, uncle to David I of Scotland; and thus his degree of kinship was more remotes as coming through the collateral line of the uncle.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] The claims of Nicholas de Soules, Patrick Galithly, William de Ros, Patrick Dunbar, William de Vesci, and Roger de Mandeville were dismissed since their claims of being descendants of King William the Lion were made through an illegitimate line.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Similarly, Robert Pinkeys claim was dismissed since his ancestor was a half-sister to King William the Lion.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] The claim Eric II, King of Norway, was also dismissed as the son-in-law of the King was not a blood relative.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] As such, by the normal rules of feudal or customary law the kingdom should be split amongst the direct descendants of the co-heiresses of David I.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Unsurprisingly, a court made up of Scots nobles rejected these arguments out of hand.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Floris V's argument was that during the reign of William the Lion the king's brother David, Earl of Huntingdon had resigned the right of himself and his heirs to the throne in exchange for a grant of land in Aberdeenshire.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] If true, this would rule out the first three claimants, all heirs of Earl David, and give Floris the strongest claim to the throne.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Floris claimed that although he did not possess copies of the documents detailing the handover of power, one must exist somewhere in Scotland, and Edward adjourned the court for a full ten months while a search was made through various castle treasuries.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] No such copy was found, and Floris withdrew his claim in the summer of 1292.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] In November 1292, following the rejection of Brus's claim, Floris then put forward his claim for a second time—this time with Brus as his backer.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] However, Floris's case was this time rejected for lack of evidence: despite the long interval since his earlier request for an adjournment, he was unable to produce evidence of his claim—due, he claimed, to theft of the vital documents.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] His claim was this time thrown out for lack of evidence.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] John Balliol had the simplest, and thus, by some measure, the strongest claim of the four.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Balliol also argued that the Kingdom of Scotland was, as a royal estate, indivisible as an entity.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] This was necessary to prevent the kingdom being split equally amongst the heirs, as Hastings argued.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Robert de Brus, Lord of Annandale, had the best claim to the throne according to proximity of blood.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] As such, his arguments centred on this being a more suitable way to govern the succession than primogeniture.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] His lawyers suggested that this had been the case in most successions and as such had become something of a "natural law".
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] They also put before the court the suggestion that Alexander III had designated Brus as heir when he himself was still childless.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Finally, his lawyers argued that the concept of primogeniture would only be relevant if customary law applied.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Strict customary law, they said, would validate Hastings' argument, and require the kingdom to be split; if the kingdom was indivisible, customary law (including primogeniture) could not apply.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Whatever the rationale for Brus's earlier nomination as heir, however, it was not considered conclusive evidence of which tradition was being followed, because at that time Devorguilla had no sons, and so Brus would have also qualified as heir by male-preference primogeniture.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] As for any apparent contradiction between accepting primogeniture and rejecting partition, Edward I was unsympathetic to the argument, having himself drawn up plans for England to be inherited by his eldest daughter, should he die without sons.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] In November 1292, therefore, Edward ruled that customary law and primogeniture rather than proximity of blood should be used to determine the rightful heir.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Finally, in the closing days of the Great Cause, Brus did an about-turn on the matter of the divisibility of the kingdom.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] This argument was swiftly rejected, and a verdict given in favour of Balliol as rightful king.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Edward delivered the judgement of the jurors on the Scottish case on 17 November 1292 in favour of John Balliol, with his son Edward Balliol becoming heir designate.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] This decision had the support of the majority of Scots nobles and magnates, even a number of those appointed by Brus as auditors.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] Of special note was the support of John II Comyn, another claimant and head of the most powerful baronial family in Scotland, who was married to Balliol's sister, Eleanor.
[src:competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland/competitors-for-the-crown-of-scotland] In later years the Comyn family remained staunch supporters of the Balliol claim to the throne.
